{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17609870","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17609870"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:54:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:54:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16133"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16133","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16133"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.34,0.31,0,0.16,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8824"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64024"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8824","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8824"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16133"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49455"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8108"},{"type":"tags","id":"10623"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21049"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21051"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64024","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64024"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EIn the first trimester of pregnancy, implantation and early placentation occur, resembling the process of tissue injury and repair. An inflammatory environment is crucial for the attachment of the blastocyst to the uterine lining.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is promoted during the first trimester of pregnancy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increase in mucins","Receptivity of maternal decidua","Decrease in blood supply to the uterus","Inhibition of immune cells","Reduction in uterine contractions"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring the first trimester, the \u003Cstrong\u003Ereceptivity of the maternal decidua\u003C/strong\u003E is promoted to facilitate the attachment and implantation of the blastocyst. This process is supported by an inflammatory environment that aids in tissue remodeling and placentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncrease in mucins\u003C/strong\u003E - While mucins play a role in the uterine lining, their increase is not specifically promoted during implantation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecrease in blood supply to the uterus\u003C/strong\u003E - Blood supply actually increases to support the growing embryo\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibition of immune cells\u003C/strong\u003E - Immune modulation occurs, but not outright inhibition\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduction in uterine contractions\u003C/strong\u003E - Uterine quiescence is important later in pregnancy, but not specifically promoted during implantation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["During the first trimester of pregnancy, the maternal decidua becomes receptive to the implanting blastocyst.","The inflammatory environment in early pregnancy is crucial for successful implantation and placentation."],"references":["Mor G, Cardenas I, Abrahams V, Guller S. Inflammation and pregnancy: the role of the immune system at the implantation site. Ann N Y Acad Sci. 2011 Mar;1221(1):80-7. doi: 10.1111/j.1749-6632.2010.05938.x. PMID: 21401634; PMCID: PMC3078586","Mor G, Cardenas I. The immune system in pregnancy: a unique complexity. Am J Reprod Immunol. 2010 Jun;63(6):425-33. doi: 10.1111/j.1600-0897.2010.00836.x. Epub 2010 Mar 29. PMID: 20367629; PMCID: PMC3025805","Abu-Raya B, Michalski C, Sadarangani M, Lavoie PM. Maternal Immunological Adaptation During Normal Pregnancy. Front Immunol. 2020 Oct 7;11:575197. doi: 10.3389/fimmu.2020.575197. PMID: 33133091; PMCID: PMC7579415","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49455"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16133"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49455","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49455"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-22T21:18:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-22T21:18:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8824"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64024"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Rememb